<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="51" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1126,267,450]" pageId="4" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,268,299,322]" pageId="4" pageNumber="51">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Distinguished from the nominotypical subgenus by the coloration, structure of the head, fore wing shape and venation, and the presence of two lateral spines on hind tibia (see the key above).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="51" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1126,267,450]" pageId="4" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,280,395,418]" pageId="4" pageNumber="51">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Greek noun “φȐpoς” (lighthouse) from which Russian equivalent of “sail” is derived (
<bibRefCitation author="MOKIENKO V. M." box="[337,512,427,450]" pageId="4" pageNumber="51" refId="ref3858" refString="MOKIENKO V. M. 2007: Zagadki russkoy frazeologii. (Riddles of Russian phraseology). Avalon Azbuka - Klassika, Sankt-Peterburg, 255 pp. (in Russian)." type="book" year="2007">MOKIENKO 2007</bibRefCitation>
). The fore wing shape of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melichar" authorityYear="1923" box="[783,913,427,450]" class="Insecta" family="Nogodinidae" genus="Orthophana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[783,913,427,450]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="51">Orthophana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
reminds a sail.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
